title: For Sale/Trade:  SOLD SOLD SOLD Norinco SKS Sporterized w/ 2 20 Rd mags
postcontent: UPDATE: a couple of you wanted to know whether this rifle is 922R compliant as it sits. YES, the gun is compliant. A Norinco SKS has 14 evil Imported parts therefore four must be changed.A US made Tapco magazine counts as two parts (Mag body and follower), US made stock counts as one part, US made handguard counts as one part. That leaves 10 Imported parts which is compliant.This is a fairly rough but perfectly functional SKS. Missing bayonet, rear leaf sight replaced with an aperture sight, stock replaced with a "combat exchange" Monte Carlo stock. Magazine is a Tapco detachable 20 rounder (two included). As the second picture shows the rifle has some rust and old, light pitting on the bolt. Luckily the bore is chrome lined, mirror bright and pristine. It functions perfectly with cheap steel case ammo.I might be over exaggerating the negatives, but I'd rather have you surprised that it's not as bad as you thought than for you to be disappointed in its condition.This is a perfect gun to give a rattle can finish and throw behind the seat of a truck or for you preppers, gloop it up with cosmoline and bury it as a bug out stash gun.$330 cash, firm. you pay transfer at your preferred FFL in Snohomish/Skagit counties. title: For Sale:  NEW CZECHPOINT VZ 61 9X18 MAKAROV PISTOL+2-20 ROUND MAGS/$35 SHIP
postcontent:
UP FOR SALE IS A BRAND NEW IN HARD CASECZECHPOINT VZ 61 9X18 MAKAROV CALIBERSEMI AUTO PISTOL+ THREADED BARRELCOMES WITH 2-20 ROUND MAGAZINESTHESE PISTOLS WORK FLAWLESSLYSPECS:Caliber 9x18 mm MakarovBarrel length 4.53 inOverall length 10.75 inWidth of pistol 1.77 inHeight of pistol with 20 rd magazine 7.10 inWeight of pistol without magazine2.54 lbsWeight of pistol with loaded 20 rd magazine3.15 lbsWeight of empty 20 rd magazine0.11 lbsWeight of full 20 rd magazine0.65 lbs
he 9x18 mm Makarov Sa vz. 61 Pistol is the semi-automatic version of the original 7.65mm Browning caliber Sa vz. 61 submachine gun.
The original Sa vz. 61 submachine gun (machine pistol) was designed in the late 1950´s in Czechoslovakia and was intended for use with reconnaissance units, tank crews, Special Forces, and for security forces of the Ministry of Interior. The vz. 61 was developed to fulfill a specific need: a firearm that could be worn like a pistol (in a holster) and capable of full automatic fire.  
9x18 mm Makarov vz. 61 Pistols utilize polycarbonate for the magazine body - specifically TARFLON IR2500.  This is an extremely tough material that is impact and wear resistant.   It is the same material used in 5.56x45 mm vz. 58 magazines.   Two magazines are included with the pistol - both the 2nd generation waffle type pattern (as shown in the photos).
HREADED BARREL INFORMATION:
The threaded barrel is 1/2x28 and includes the thread protector. CzechPoint worked with Czech Small Arms to develop a threaded barrel that does not utilize a thread adapter. This was accomplished by enlarging the outside diameter (O.D.) of the barrel which requires enlarging the trunnion hole diameter that accepts the barrel. The barrel O.D. was enlarged to the fullest extent, but ultimately the O.D. is limited due to the size of the trunnion. The outside diameter of the barrel measures .550 inches so there is a shoulder for indexing a sound suppressor. Czech Small Arms used the thread guide from Advanced Armament Corp. to design this threaded barrel.

title: For Sale:  NEW CZECHPOINT VZ 61 380 ACP PISTOL+2-20 ROUND MAGS/$35 SHIP
postcontent:
UP FOR SALE IS A BRAND NEW IN HARD CASECZECHPOINT VZ 61 380 ACP SEMI AUTO PISTOLCOMES WITH 2-20 ROUND MAGAZINES, PIC RAIL, & CASESPECS:Caliber .380 AutoBarrel length 4.53 inOverall length 10.75 inWidth of pistol1.77 inHeight of pistol with 20 rd magazine 7.10 inWeight of pistol without magazine2.67 lbsWeight of pistol with loaded 20 rd magazine3.28 lbsWeight of empty 20 rd magazine0.11 lbsWeight of full 20 rd magazine0.55 lbs
The .380 Auto Sa vz. 61 Pistol is the semi-automatic version of the original 7.65mm Browning caliber Sa vz. 61 submachine gun.  This model possesses a Picatinny rail under the barrel for mounting a flash light or laser.
The original Sa vz. 61 submachine gun (machine pistol) was designed in the late 1950´s in Czechoslovakia and was intended for use with reconnaissance units, tank crews, Special Forces, and for security forces of the Ministry of Interior. The vz. 61 was developed to fulfill a specific need: a firearm that could be worn like a pistol (in a holster) and capable of full automatic fire.  
.380 Auto vz. 61 Pistols utilize polycarbonate for the magazine body - specifically TARFLON IR2500.  This is an extremely tough material that is impact and wear resistant.   It is the same material used in 5.56x45 mm vz. 58 magazines.   Two magazines are included with the pistol - both the 2nd generation waffle type pattern (as shown in the photos).
The design of the Sa vz. 61 submachine gun was unique in its time. It uses the following common operational features found on a submachine gun: an unlocked bolt, magazine inserted into the bottom of the receiver (outside of the pistol grip) and a folding stock. These common features are combined with the following characteristics not usually found in submachine guns: extraordinary small size, fires from a closed bolt, and uses a rate reducer to slow full automatic fire.

title: For Trade:  Very rare Osgood Gun Works Duplex revolver
postcontent:
This is for a very rare revolver, the Osgood Gun Works Duplex which was made around 1880 and there were only about 300 manufactured. It is a nickel-plated revolver with black hard rubber grips, it has a 22/32 caliber cylinder/barrels. It holds eight 22 and is a single shot 32. Right now I am putting it out there to see what I can get for it. Please do not be afraid to make me an offer of anything for trade or a cash offer. I could be interested in anything but my weakness is revolvers.  The following is the information I could find on it:
Object Description:
OSGOOD WORKS REVOLVER DUPLEX .22/.32Manufactured by Osgood Gun Works, Norwich, Ct. - Osgood Works hinged-frame revolver with fluted cylinder. Based on a cross between Smith & Wesson and a LeMat. Two barrel .22 over a .32. Cylinder has eight .22 caliber chambers around the circumference and a .32 rf in the center which doubles as the cylinder axis pin. The .32 fires out of the lower barrel. Checkered hard rubber grips. Weapon weighs approximately 8.1 oz.Markings:Barrel: PAT'D DEC. 7, 1880. (Left): OSGOOD GUN WORKS, NORWICH, CONN. Top strap: DUPLEX.Notes: About 300 of these manufactured in 1880s."Osgood Gun Works - Norwich, Ct. Makers of 'Duplex' and 'Monarch' rimfire revolvers, 1880-83."The Osgood Gun Works of Norwich, Connecticut, was formed in 1880 for the sole purpose of making this revolver; the partnership between financial backer Osgood and patentee Freeman W. Hood failed in 1882 as a result of poor sales. The Duplex revolver was a modernized version of the better known Le Mat of the Civil War period, which had carried a shotgun charge in a separate central barrel forming the cylinder axis pin. Eight-shot single action hinged frame .22 Short rimfire Duplex guns have an additional .32 calibre barrel - forming the cylinder arbor - which extends back through the frame to chamber a single .32 Short rimfire cartridge. The hammer had a moveable firing pin; set in the upper position it fired the .22 cartridges in the cylinder chambers in the usual manner. When switched to the lower position it fired the .32 cartridge in the lower barrel. The lack of any form of automatic extraction was a drawback. A strap hinged to the barrel in front of the cylinder, which snapped over the standing breech, was a poor frame-latch; it was probably defective enough when new - but soon developed a dangerous amount of play.Duplex revolvers are scarce and unusual. They are generally marked DUPLEX PAT DEC 7 1880; they may also display OSGOOD GUN WORKS.

The Sa vz. 61 was designed for reconnaissance units, tank crews, Special Forces, and for security forces of the Ministry of Interior. The Sa vz. 61 was developed to fulfill a specific need: a firearm that could be worn like a pistol (in a holster) and capable of full automatic fire.The design of the Sa vz. 61 was unique in its time. It uses the following common operational features found on a submachine gun: an unlocked bolt, magazine inserted into the bottom of the receiver (outside of the pistol grip) and a folding stock. These common features are combined with the following characteristics not usually found in submachine guns: extraordinary small size, fires from a closed bolt, and uses a rate reducer to slow full automatic fire.The Sa vz. 61 offered by CzechPoint is the semi-automatic version of the original military issued firearm - it is as close as one can get to owning the legendary vz. 61 submachine gun.
